    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#gasparini-rosamilia2016"/>, n. <citedRange>2</citedRange> (fig. 18)</bibl>, whence
                <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>66.2332</citedRange></bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>133400</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Eumenis"><name nymRef="#Εὐμενίς"><supplied reason="lost">Εὐμεν</supplied>ίδι</name></persName> 
                    <persName type="divine" ref="#Zeus_Melichios"><rs type="epithet" key="Melichios"><name nymRef="#Μηλίχιος">Μ<unclear>ηλιχ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ίωι</supplied></name></rs></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pour l'Euménide, pour Mèlikhios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>For the Eumenide, for Melichios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Per l'Eumenide, per Melichios.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Zeus Melichios is here named only with his epithet. However there is no reason to think that this became a divine name by itself.</p>
	  <p>The use of the dative is unique on such altars. Only this mention deserves fully to be said 'dedication', a term which we took conventionally for 
	           the many other instances with the genitive.</p>
	<p>For a Eumenide at the singular see also <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr133800</ref>.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
